[3113.23678, "o", "\u001b[4mSYSTEMCTL\u001b[24m(1)                          systemctl                         \u001b[4mSYSTEMCTL\u001b[24m(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       systemctl - Control the systemd system and service manager\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1msystemctl \u001b[22m[OPTIONS...] COMMAND [UNIT...]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1msystemctl \u001b[22mmay be used to introspect and control the state of the \"systemd\"\u001b[m\r\n       system and service manager. Please refer to \u001b[1msystemd\u001b[22m(1) for an introduction\u001b[m\r\n       into the basic concepts and functionality this tool manages.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The following commands are understood:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mUnit Commands (Introspection and Modification)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3114.136398, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1mlist-units \u001b[22m[\u001b[4mPATTERN\u001b[24m...]\u001b[m\r\n           List units that \u001b[1msystemd \u001b[22mcurrently has in memory. This includes units that\u001b[m\r\n           are either referenced directly or through a dependency, units that are\u001b[m\r\n           pinned by applications programmatically, or units that were active in the\u001b[m\r\n           past and have failed. By default only units which are active, have\u001b[m\r\n           pending jobs, or have failed are shown; this can be changed with option\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1m--all\u001b[22m. If one or more \u001b[4mPATTERN\u001b[24ms are specified, only units matching one of\u001b[m\r\n           them are shown. The units that are shown are additionally filtered by\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1m--type= \u001b[22mand \u001b[1m--state= \u001b[22mif those options are specified.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Note that this command does not show unit templates, but only instances\u001b[m\r\n           of unit templates. Units templates that aren't instantiated are not\u001b[m\r\n           runnable, and will thus never show up in the output of this co"]
[3114.136527, "o", "mmand.\u001b[m\r\n           Specifically this means that foo@.service will never be shown in this\u001b[m\r\n           list — unless instantiated, e.g. as foo@bar.service. Use \u001b[1mlist-unit-files\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           (see below) for listing installed unit template files.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Produces output similar to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 19 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3114.608632, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n                 UNIT                         LOAD   ACTIVE SUB     DESCRIPTION\u001b[m\r\n                 sys-module-fuse.device       loaded active plugged /sys/module/fuse\u001b[m\r\n                 -.mount                      loaded active mounted Root Mount\u001b[m"]
[3114.608823, "o", "\r\n                 boot-efi.mount               loaded active mounted /boot/efi\u001b[m\r\n                 systemd-journald.service     loaded active running Journal Service\u001b[m\r\n                 systemd-logind.service       loaded active running Login Service\u001b[m\r\n               ● user@1000.service            loaded failed failed  User Manager for UI\u001b[m \bD 1000\u001b[m\r\n                 ...\u001b[m\r\n                 systemd-tmpfiles-clean.timer loaded active waiting Daily Cleanup of Te\u001b[m \bmporary Directories\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n               LOAD   = Reflects whether the unit definition was properly loaded.\u001b[m\r\n               ACTIVE = The high-level unit activation state, i.e. generalization of SU\u001b[m \bB.\u001b[m\r\n               SUB    = The low-level unit activation state, values depend on unit type\u001b[m \b.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 37 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3115.627329, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n               123 loaded units listed. Pass --all to see loaded but inactive units, to\u001b[m \bo.\u001b[m\r\n               To show all installed unit files use 'systemctl list-unit-files'.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           The header and the last unit of a given type are underlined if the\u001b[m\r\n           terminal supports that. A colored dot is shown next to services which\u001b[m\r\n           were masked, not found, or otherwise failed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           The LOAD column shows the load state, one of \u001b[1mloaded\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mnot-found\u001b[22m,\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1mbad-setting\u001b[22m, \u001b[1merror\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mmasked\u001b[22m. The ACTIVE columns shows the general unit\u001b[m\r\n           state, one of \u001b[1mactive\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mreloading\u001b[22m, \u001b[1minactive\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mfailed\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mactivating\u001b[22m,\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1mdeactivating\u001b[22m. The SUB column shows the unit-type-specific detailed state\u001b[m\r\n           of the unit, possible values vary by unit type. The list of possible\u001b[m\r\n           LOAD, ACTIVE, and SUB states is not constant and new systemd releases "]
[3115.627365, "o", "may\u001b[m\r\n           both add and remove values.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n               systemctl --state=help\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 51 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3116.117241, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m"]
[3116.117408, "o", "\r\n           command may be used to display the current set of possible values.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           This is the default command.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mlist-automounts \u001b[22m[\u001b[4mPATTERN\u001b[24m...]\u001b[m\r\n           List automount units currently in memory, ordered by mount path. If one\u001b[m\r\n           or more \u001b[4mPATTERN\u001b[24ms are specified, only automount units matching one of them\u001b[m\r\n           are shown. Produces output similar to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n               WHAT        WHERE                    MOUNTED IDLE TIMEOUT UNIT\u001b[m\r\n               /dev/sdb1   /mnt/test                no      120s         mnt-test.autom\u001b[m \bount\u001b[m\r\n               binfmt_misc /proc/sys/fs/binfmt_misc yes     0            proc-sys-fs-bi\u001b[m \bnfmt_misc.automount\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n               2 automounts listed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 68 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3116.783118, "o", "\r\u001b[K           Also see \u001b[1m--show-types\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--all\u001b[22m, and \u001b[1m--state=\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 252.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mlist-paths \u001b[22m[\u001b[4mPATTERN\u001b[24m...]\u001b[m\r\n           List path units currently in memory, ordered by path. If one or more\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mPATTERN\u001b[24ms are specified, only path units matching one of them are shown.\u001b[m\r\n           Produces output similar to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n               PATH                           CONDITION         UNIT                   \u001b[m \b            ACTIVATES\u001b[m\r\n               /run/systemd/ask-password      DirectoryNotEmpty systemd-ask-password-pl\u001b[m \bymouth.path systemd-ask-password-plymouth.service\u001b[m\r\n               /run/systemd/ask-password      DirectoryNotEmpty systemd-ask-password-wa\u001b[m \bll.path     systemd-ask-password-wall.service\u001b[m\r\n               /var/cache/cups/org.cups.cupsd PathExists        cups.path              \u001b[m \b            cups.service\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 84 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b"]
[3116.783221, "o", "[K"]
[3117.458033, "o", "\r\u001b[K               3 paths listed.\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3117.458303, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n           Also see \u001b[1m--show-types\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--all\u001b[22m, and \u001b[1m--state=\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 254.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mlist-sockets \u001b[22m[\u001b[4mPATTERN\u001b[24m...]\u001b[m\r\n           List socket units currently in memory, ordered by listening address. If\u001b[m\r\n           one or more \u001b[4mPATTERN\u001b[24ms are specified, only socket units matching one of\u001b[m\r\n           them are shown. Produces output similar to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n               LISTEN           UNIT                        ACTIVATES\u001b[m\r\n               /dev/initctl     systemd-initctl.socket      systemd-initctl.service\u001b[m\r\n               ...\u001b[m\r\n               [::]:22          sshd.socket                 sshd.service\u001b[m\r\n               kobject-uevent 1 systemd-udevd-kernel.socket systemd-udevd.service\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n               5 sockets listed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 98 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3117.922796, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n           Note: because the addresses might contains spaces, this output is not\u001b[m"]
[3117.922954, "o", "\r\n           suitable for programmatic consumption.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Also see \u001b[1m--show-types\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--all\u001b[22m, and \u001b[1m--state=\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 202.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mlist-timers \u001b[22m[\u001b[4mPATTERN\u001b[24m...]\u001b[m\r\n           List timer units currently in memory, ordered by the time they elapse\u001b[m\r\n           next. If one or more \u001b[4mPATTERN\u001b[24ms are specified, only units matching one of\u001b[m\r\n           them are shown. Produces output similar to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n               NEXT                         LEFT          LAST                         \u001b[m \bPASSED     UNIT                         ACTIVATES\u001b[m\r\n               -                            -             Thu 2017-02-23 13:40:29 EST  \u001b[m \b3 days ago ureadahead-stop.timer        ureadahead-stop.service\u001b[m\r\n               Sun 2017-02-26 18:55:42 EST  1min 14s left Thu 2017-02-23 13:54:44 EST  \u001b[m \b\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 116 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3118.35116, "o", "\r\u001b[K3 days ago systemd-tmpfiles-clean.timer systemd-tmpfiles-clean.service\u001b[m\r\n               Sun 2017-02-26 20:37:16 EST  1h 42min left Sun 2017-02-26 11:56:36 EST  \u001b[m \b6h ago     apt-daily.timer              apt-daily.service\u001b[m\r\n               Sun 2017-02-26 20:57:49 EST  2h 3min left  Sun 2017-02-26 11:56:36 EST  \u001b[m \b6h ago     snapd.refresh.timer          snapd.refresh.service\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mNEXT\u001b[24m shows the next time the timer will run.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mLEFT\u001b[24m shows how long till the next time the timer runs.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mLAST\u001b[24m shows the last time the timer ran.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mPASSED\u001b[24m shows how long has passed since the timer last ran.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mUNIT\u001b[24m shows the name of the timer\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mACTIVATES\u001b[24m shows the name the service the timer activates when it runs.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 131 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3118.921909, "o", "\r\u001b[K           Also see \u001b[1m--all \u001b[22mand \u001b[1m--state=\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 209.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mis-active \u001b[4m\u001b[22mPATTERN\u001b[24m\u001b[1m...\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Check whether any of the specified units are active (i.e. running).\u001b[m\r\n           Returns an exit code \u001b[1m0 \u001b[22mif at least one is active, or non-zero otherwise.\u001b[m\r\n           Unless \u001b[1m--quiet \u001b[22mis specified, this will also print the current unit state\u001b[m\r\n           to standard output.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mis-failed [\u001b[4m\u001b[22mPATTERN\u001b[24m...]\u001b[m\r\n           Check whether any of the specified units is in the \"failed\" state. If no\u001b[m\r\n           unit is specified, check whether there are any failed units, which\u001b[m"]
[3118.922084, "o", "\r\n           corresponds to the \"degraded\" state returned by \u001b[1mis-system-running\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n           Returns an exit code \u001b[1m0 \u001b[22mif at least one has failed, non-zero otherwise.\u001b[m\r\n           Unless \u001b[1m--quiet \u001b[22mis specified, this will also print the current unit or\u001b[m\r\n           system state to standard output.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 147 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3119.221626, "o", "\r\u001b[K           Added in version 197.\u001b[m"]
[3119.221657, "o", "\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mstatus \u001b[22m[\u001b[4mPATTERN\u001b[24m...|\u001b[4mPID\u001b[24m...]]\u001b[m\r\n           Show runtime status information about the whole system or about one or\u001b[m\r\n           more units followed by most recent log data from the journal. If no\u001b[m\r\n           positional arguments are specified, and no unit filter is given with\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1m--type=\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--state=\u001b[22m, or \u001b[1m--failed\u001b[22m, shows the status of the whole system. If\u001b[m\r\n           combined with \u001b[1m--all\u001b[22m, follows that with the status of all units. If\u001b[m\r\n           positional arguments are specified, each positional argument is treated\u001b[m\r\n           as either a unit name to show, or a glob pattern to show units whose\u001b[m\r\n           names match that pattern, or a PID to show the unit containing that PID.\u001b[m\r\n           When \u001b[1m--type=\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--state=\u001b[22m, or \u001b[1m--failed \u001b[22mare used, units are additionally\u001b[m\r\n           filtered by the TYPE and ACTIVE state.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           This function is intended to generate human-readable"]
[3119.221671, "o", " output. If you are\u001b[m\r\n           looking for computer-parsable output, use \u001b[1mshow \u001b[22minstead. By default, this\u001b[m\r\n           function only shows 10 lines of output and ellipsizes lines to fit in the\u001b[m\r\n           terminal window. This can be changed with \u001b[1m--lines \u001b[22mand \u001b[1m--full\u001b[22m, see above.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 165 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3119.467507, "o", "\r\u001b[K           In addition, \u001b[1mjournalctl --unit=\u001b[4m\u001b[22mNAME\u001b[24m or \u001b[1mjournalctl --user-unit=\u001b[4m\u001b[22mNAME\u001b[24m use a\u001b[m\r\n           similar filter for messages and might be more convenient.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Note that this operation only displays \u001b[4mruntime\u001b[24m status, i.e. information\u001b[m\r\n           about the current invocation of the unit (if it is running) or the most\u001b[m\r\n           recent invocation (if it is not running anymore, and has not been\u001b[m\r\n           released from memory). Information about earlier invocations, invocations\u001b[m\r\n           from previous system boots, or prior invocations that have already been\u001b[m\r\n           released from memory may be retrieved via \u001b[1mjournalctl --unit=\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           systemd implicitly loads units as necessary, so just running the \u001b[1mstatus\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           will attempt to load a file. The command is thus not useful for\u001b[m\r\n           determining if something was already loaded or not. The units may\u001b[m\r\n           possibly also be quic"]
[3119.467625, "o", "kly unloaded after the operation is completed if\u001b[m\r\n"]
[3119.467695, "o", "           there's no reason to keep it in memory thereafter.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1mExample 1. Example output from systemctl status\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 183 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3119.647872, "o", "\r\u001b[K               $ systemctl status bluetooth\u001b[m\r\n               ● bluetooth.service - Bluetooth service\u001b[m\r\n                  Loaded: loaded (/usr/lib/systemd/system/bluetooth.service; enabled; p\u001b[m \breset: enabled)\u001b[m\r\n                  Active: active (running) since Wed 2017-01-04 13:54:04 EST; 1 weeks 0\u001b[m \b days ago\u001b[m\r\n                    Docs: man:bluetoothd(8)\u001b[m\r\n                Main PID: 930 (bluetoothd)\u001b[m\r\n                  Status: \"Running\"\u001b[m\r\n                   Tasks: 1\u001b[m\r\n                  Memory: 648.0K\u001b[m\r\n                     CPU: 435ms\u001b[m\r\n                  CGroup: /system.slice/bluetooth.service\u001b[m\r\n                          └─930 /usr/lib/bluetooth/bluetoothd\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n               Jan 12 10:46:45 example.com bluetoothd[8900]: Not enough free handles to\u001b[m \b register service\u001b[m\r\n               Jan 12 10:46:45 example.com bluetoothd[8900]: Current Time Service could\u001b[m \b\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 201 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3119.812557, "o", "\r\u001b[K not be registered\u001b[m\r\n               Jan 12 10:46:45 example.com bluetoothd[8900]: gatt-time-server: Input/ou\u001b[m \btput error (5)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           The dot (\"●\") uses color on supported terminals to summarize the unit\u001b[m\r\n           state at a glance. Along with its color, its shape varies according to\u001b[m"]
[3119.812643, "o", "\r\n           its state: \"inactive\" or \"maintenance\" is a white circle (\"○\"), \"active\"\u001b[m\r\n           is a green dot (\"●\"), \"deactivating\" is a white dot, \"failed\" or \"error\"\u001b[m\r\n           is a red cross (\"×\"), and \"reloading\" is a green clockwise circle arrow\u001b[m\r\n           (\"↻\").\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           The \"Loaded:\" line in the output will show \"loaded\" if the unit has been\u001b[m\r\n           loaded into memory. Other possible values for \"Loaded:\" include: \"error\"\u001b[m\r\n           if there was a problem loading it, \"not-found\" if no unit file was found\u001b[m\r\n           for this unit, \"bad-setting\" if an essential unit file setting could not\u001b[m\r\n           be parsed and \"masked\" if the unit file has been masked. Along with\u001b[m\r\n           showing the path to the unit file, this line will also show the\u001b[m\r\n           enablement state. Enabled units are included in the dependency network\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 215 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3120.810955, "o", "\r\u001b[K/"]
[3121.119405, "o", "\u001b[Ks\bs"]
[3121.329629, "o", "\u001b[Kt\bt"]
[3121.55444, "o", "\u001b[Ka\ba"]
[3121.74166, "o", "\u001b[Kt\bt"]
[3121.816729, "o", "\u001b[Ku\bu"]
[3121.959497, "o", "\u001b[Ks\bs"]
[3122.094037, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[1;1H not be registered\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H               Jan 12 10:46:45 example.com bluetoothd[8900]: gatt-time-server: Input/ou\u001b[m \b\u001b[3;1Htput error (5)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[m"]
[3122.094502, "o", "\r\n\u001b[5;1H           The dot (\"●\") uses color on supported terminals to summarize the unit\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H           state at a glance. Along with its color, its shape varies according to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H           its state: \"inactive\" or \"maintenance\" is a white circle (\"○\"), \"active\"\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H           is a green dot (\"●\"), \"deactivating\" is a white dot, \"failed\" or \"error\"\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H           is a red cross (\"×\"), and \"reloading\" is a green clockwise circle arrow\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H           (\"↻\").\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H           The \"Loaded:\" line in the output will show \"loaded\" if the unit has been\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H           loaded into memory. Other possible values for \"Loaded:\" include: \"error\"\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H           if there was a problem loading it, \"not-found\" if no unit file was found\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H           for this unit, \"bad-setting\" if an essential unit file setting could not\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H           be parsed and \"masked\" if the unit file has been masked. Along with\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H           showing the path to "]
[3122.094516, "o", "the unit file, this line will also show the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H           enablement state. Enabled units are included in the dependency network\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H\u001b[1;1H not be registered\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H               Jan 12 10:46:45 example.com bluetoothd[8900]: gatt-time-server: Input/ou\u001b[m \b\u001b[3;1Htput error (5)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H           The dot (\"●\") uses color on supported terminals to summarize the unit\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H           state at a glance. Along with its color, its shape varies according to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H           its state: \"inactive\" or \"maintenance\" is a white circle (\"○\"), \"active\"\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H           is a green dot (\"●\"), \"deactivating\" is a white dot, \"failed\" or \"error\"\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H           is a red cross (\"×\"), and \"reloading\" is a green clockwise circle arrow\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H           (\"↻\").\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H           The \"Loaded:\" line in the output will show \"loaded\" if the unit has been\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H           loaded into memory. Other possible values for \"Loaded:\" include: \"error\"\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H  "]
[3122.094521, "o", "         if there was a problem loading it, \"not-found\" if no unit file was found\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H           for this unit, \"bad-setting\" if an essential unit file setting could not\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H           be parsed and \"masked\" if the unit file has been masked. Along with\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H           showing the path to the unit file, this line will also show the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H           enablement state. Enabled units are included in the dependency network\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[19;1H...skipping...\r\n           whenever computer-parsable output is required. Use \u001b[1m\u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m\u001b[1m \u001b[22mif you are\u001b[m\r\n           looking for formatted human-readable output.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Many properties shown by \u001b[1msystemctl show \u001b[22mmap directly to configuration\u001b[m\r\n           settings of the system and service manager and its unit files. Note that\u001b[m\r\n           the properties shown by the command are generally more low-level,\u001b[m\r\n           normalized versions of the original configuration settings and expose\u001b[m\r\n           runtime state in addi"]
[3122.094525, "o", "tion to configuration. For example, properties shown\u001b[m\r\n           for service units include the service's current main process identifier\u001b[m\r\n           as \"MainPID\" (which is runtime state), and time settings are always\u001b[m\r\n           exposed as properties ending in the \"...USec\" suffix even if a matching\u001b[m\r\n           configuration options end in \"...Sec\", because microseconds is the\u001b[m\r\n           normalized time unit used internally by the system and service manager.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           For details about many of these properties, see the documentation of the\u001b[m\r\n           D-Bus interface backing these properties, see\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1morg.freedesktop.systemd1\u001b[22m(5).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 252 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3122.897057, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K...skipping...\r\n           code and \u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m is recorded for introspection by the administrator until\u001b[m\r\n           the service is stopped/re-started or reset with this command.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           In addition to resetting the \"failed\" state of a unit it also resets\u001b[m\r\n           various other per-unit properties: the start rate limit counter of all\u001b[m\r\n           unit types is reset to zero, as is the restart counter of service units.\u001b[m\r\n           Thus, if a unit's start limit (as configured with\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mStartLimitIntervalSec=\u001b[24m/\u001b[4mStartLimitBurst=\u001b[24m) is hit and the unit refuses to\u001b[m\r\n           be started again, use this command to make it startable again.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mwhoami [\u001b[4m\u001b[22mPID\u001b[24m\u001b[1m...]\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Returns the units the processes referenced by the given PIDs belong to\u001b[m\r\n           (one per line). If no PID is specified returns the unit the \u001b[1msystemctl\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           command is invoked in.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 254.\u001b["]
[3122.897077, "o", "m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mUnit File Commands\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 575 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3123.429769, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K...skipping...\r\n           Reset the enable/disable \u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m one or more unit files, as specified on\u001b[m\r\n           the command line, to the defaults configured in the preset policy files.\u001b[m\r\n           This has the same effect as \u001b[1mdisable \u001b[22mor \u001b[1menable\u001b[22m, depending how the unit is\u001b[m\r\n           listed in the preset files.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Use \u001b[1m--preset-mode= \u001b[22mto control whether units shall be enabled and\u001b[m\r\n           disabled, or only enabled, or only disabled.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           If the unit carries no install information, it will be silently ignored\u001b[m\r\n           by this command.  \u001b[4mUNIT\u001b[24m must be the real unit name, any alias names are\u001b[m\r\n           ignored silently.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           For more information on the preset policy format, see \u001b[1msystemd.preset\u001b[22m(5).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 238.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mpreset-all\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Resets all installed unit files to the defaults configured in the preset\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemct"]
[3123.429788, "o", "l(1) line 713 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3123.83404, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K...skipping...\r\n           otherwise. Prints the current enable \u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m (see table). To suppress this\u001b[m\r\n           output, use \u001b[1m--quiet\u001b[22m. To show installation targets, use \u001b[1m--full\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1mTable 1.  is-enabled output\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           ┌───────────────────┬─────────────────────────┬───────────┐\u001b[m\r\n           │ \u001b[1mName              \u001b[22m│ \u001b[1mDescription             \u001b[22m│ \u001b[1mExit Code \u001b[22m│\u001b[m\r\n           ├───────────────────┼─────────────────────────┼───────────┤\u001b[m\r\n           │ \"enabled\"         │ Enabled via .wants/,    │           │\u001b[m\r\n           ├───────────────────┤ .requires/ or \u001b[4mAlias=\u001b[24m    │           │\u001b[m\r\n           │ \"enabled-runtime\" │ sym"]
[3123.834126, "o", "links (permanently   │           │\u001b[m\r\n           │                   │ in                      │ 0         │\u001b[m\r\n           │                   │ /etc/systemd/system/,   │           │\u001b[m\r\n           │                   │ or transiently in       │           │\u001b[m\r\n           │                   │ /run/systemd/system/).  │           │\u001b[m\r\n           ├───────────────────┼─────────────────────────┼───────────┤\u001b[m\r\n           │ \"linked\"          │ Made available through  │           │\u001b[m\r\n           ├───────────────────┤ one or more symlinks    │           │\u001b[m\r\n           │ \"linked-runtime\"  │ to the unit file        │           │\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 741 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3124.314947, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K...skipping...\r\n           the current state and returning the appropriate error \u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m. If \u001b[1m--wait\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           is in use, states \u001b[4minitializing\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mstarting\u001b[24m will not be reported, instead\u001b[m\r\n           the command will block until a later state (such as \u001b[4mrunning\u001b[24m or \u001b[4mdegraded\u001b[24m)\u001b[m\r\n           is reached.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1mTable 2. is-system-running output\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           ┌──────────────┬───────────────────────┬───────────┐\u001b[m\r\n           │ \u001b[1mName         \u001b[22m│ \u001b[1mDescription           \u001b[22m│ \u001b[1mExit Code \u001b[22m│\u001b[m\r\n           ├──────────────┼───────────────────────┼───────────┤\u001b[m\r\n           │ \u001b[4minitializing\u001b[24m │ Early bootup, before  │ > 0       │\u001b[m\r\n           │              │ basic.target is       │     "]
[3124.314978, "o", "      │\u001b[m\r\n           │              │ reached or the        │           │\u001b[m\r\n           │              │ \u001b[4mmaintenance\u001b[24m state     │           │\u001b[m\r\n           │              │ entered.              │           │\u001b[m\r\n           ├──────────────┼───────────────────────┼───────────┤\u001b[m\r\n           │ \u001b[4mstarting\u001b[24m     │ Late bootup, before   │ > 0       │\u001b[m\r\n           │              │ the job queue becomes │           │\u001b[m\r\n           │              │ idle for the first    │           │\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 1103 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3124.690703, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K...skipping...\r\n           # systemctl \u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m /dev/sda\u001b[m\r\n           # systemctl \u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m /home\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       are equivalent to:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           # systemctl \u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m dev-sda.device\u001b[m\r\n           # systemctl \u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m home.mount\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       In the second case, shell-style globs will be matched against the primary\u001b[m\r\n       names of all units currently in memory; literal unit names, with or without a\u001b[m\r\n       suffix, will be treated as in the first case. This means that literal unit\u001b[m\r\n       names always refer to exactly one unit, but globs may match zero units and\u001b[m\r\n       this is not considered an error.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Glob patterns use \u001b[1mfnmatch\u001b[22m(3), so normal shell-style globbing rules are used,\u001b[m\r\n       and \"*\", \"?\", \"[]\" may be used. See \u001b[1mglob\u001b[22m(7) for more details. The patterns\u001b[m\r\n       are matched against the primary names of units currently in memory, and\u001b[m\r\n       patterns which do not match anything are silently skipped. For e"]
[3124.690729, "o", "xample:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 1354 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3125.191371, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K\u001b[m"]
[3125.191497, "o", "\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 1355 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3125.536471, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K           # systemctl stop sshd@*.service\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       will stop all sshd@.service instances. Note that alias names of units, and\u001b[m\r\n       units that aren't in memory are not considered for glob expansion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 1359 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3125.844489, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 1360 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3126.121515, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K...skipping...\r\n           or \u001b[1m\u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m\u001b[22m, only units of the specified types will be shown. By default,\u001b[m\r\n           units of all types are shown.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           As a special case, if one of the arguments is \u001b[1mhelp\u001b[22m, a list of allowed\u001b[m\r\n           values will be printed and the program will exit.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--state=\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           The argument is a comma-separated list of unit LOAD, SUB, or ACTIVE\u001b[m\r\n           states. When listing units with \u001b[1mlist-units\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mlist-dependencies\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mshow \u001b[22mor\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1m\u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m\u001b[22m, show only those in the specified states. Use \u001b[1m--state=failed \u001b[22mor\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1m--failed \u001b[22mto show only failed units.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           As a special case, if one of the arguments is \u001b[1mhelp\u001b[22m, a list of allowed\u001b[m\r\n           values will be printed and the program will exit.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 206.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-p\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--property=\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1"]
[3126.121541, "o", ") line 1394 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3126.444885, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K           When showing unit/job/manager properties with the \u001b[1mshow \u001b[22mcommand, limit\u001b[m\r\n           display to properties specified in the argument. The argument should be a\u001b[m\r\n           comma-separated list of property names, such as \"MainPID\". Unless\u001b[m\r\n           specified, all known properties are shown. If specified more than once,\u001b[m\r\n           all properties with the specified names are shown. Shell completion is\u001b[m\r\n           implemented for property names.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           For the manager itself, \u001b[1msystemctl show \u001b[22mwill show all available\u001b[m\r\n           properties, most of which are derived or closely match the options\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 1403 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3126.932033, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K...skipping...\r\n           When used with \u001b[1m\u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m\u001b[22m, show journal messages in full, even if they\u001b[m\r\n           include unprintable characters or are very long. By default, fields with\u001b[m\r\n           unprintable characters are abbreviated as \"blob data\". (Note that the\u001b[m\r\n           pager may escape unprintable characters again.)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-r\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--recursive\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           When listing units, also show units of local containers. Units of local\u001b[m\r\n           containers will be prefixed with the container name, separated by a\u001b[m\r\n           single colon character (\":\").\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 212.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--reverse\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Show reverse dependencies between units with \u001b[1mlist-dependencies\u001b[22m, i.e.\u001b[m\r\n           follow dependencies of type \u001b[4mWantedBy=\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mRequiredBy=\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mUpheldBy=\u001b[24m, \u001b[4mPartOf=\u001b[24m,\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mBoundBy=\u001b[24m, instead of \u001b[4mWants=\u001b[24m and similar.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version "]
[3126.932056, "o", "203.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 1448 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3127.367314, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K...skipping...\r\n           When used with \u001b[1m\u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mcat\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mlist-units\u001b[22m, and \u001b[1mlist-unit-files\u001b[22m, those\u001b[m\r\n           commands print all specified units and the dependencies of those units.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Options \u001b[1m--reverse\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--after\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--before \u001b[22mmay be used to change what types of\u001b[m\r\n           dependencies are shown.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 245.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-l\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--full\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Do not ellipsize unit names, process tree entries, journal output, or\u001b[m\r\n           truncate unit descriptions in the output of \u001b[1m\u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mlist-units\u001b[22m,\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1mlist-jobs\u001b[22m, and \u001b[1mlist-timers\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Also, show installation targets in the output of \u001b[1mis-enabled\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--value\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           When printing properties with \u001b[1mshow\u001b[22m, only print the value, and skip the\u001b[m\r\n           property name and \"=\". Also see option \u001b[1m-P \u001b[22mabove.\u001b[m"]
[3127.36734, "o", "\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 1499 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3127.7198, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 230.\u001b[m"]
[3127.71997, "o", "\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--show-types\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           When showing sockets, show the type of the socket.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 202.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--job-mode=\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           When queuing a new job, this option controls how to deal with already\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 1509 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3128.080522, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K...skipping...\r\n           When used with \u001b[1m\u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m\u001b[22m, controls the number of journal lines to show,\u001b[m\r\n           counting from the most recent ones. Takes a positive integer argument, or\u001b[m\r\n           0 to disable journal output. Defaults to 10.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-o\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--output=\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           When used with \u001b[1m\u001b[7mstatus\u001b[27m\u001b[22m, controls the formatting of the journal entries\u001b[m\r\n           that are shown. For the available choices, see \u001b[1mjournalctl\u001b[22m(1). Defaults to\u001b[m\r\n           \"short\".\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--firmware-setup\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           When used with the \u001b[1mreboot\u001b[22m, \u001b[1mpoweroff\u001b[22m, or \u001b[1mhalt \u001b[22mcommand, indicate to the\u001b[m\r\n           system's firmware to reboot into the firmware setup interface for the\u001b[m\r\n           next boot. Note that this functionality is not available on all systems.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Added in version 220.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--boot-loader-menu=\u001b[4m\u001b[22mtimeout\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           When used with the \u001b[1mreboot\u001b[22m, \u001b"]
[3128.080541, "o", "[1mpoweroff\u001b[22m, or \u001b[1mhalt \u001b[22mcommand, indicate to the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 1845 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[3128.626098, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K           system's boot loader to show the boot loader menu on the following boot.\u001b[m\r\n           Takes a time value as parameter — indicating the menu timeout. Pass zero\u001b[m\r\n           in order to disable the menu timeout. Note that not all boot loaders\u001b[m\r\n           support this functionality.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page systemctl(1) line 1850 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
